<p>
      This interview, features two Indigenous organizers who are working in oklahoma. Jodran Harmon, a Muscogee Nation resident, and Chey morgan, a United Keetoowah Band of Cherokee Indian Community organizer, estabilshes what they do. They run a series of town halls across Oklahoma where there goal is to educate people about data centers and hyperscale data centers. Using that initial knowledge to then explain the horrible affects it has on the regular person. They also educate citizens on what the proccess are for how these data centers are built, and advocate for stricter guidelines in building them. As mentioned before, they edcuate the general public as well as inform them of secret deals between companies and their community representatives. Either be being forced into an unfair strongmanned NDA, or monitarly corrupt leaders who only seek to gain from it. 
</p>


<p id="topicFourMore" style="display: none;">
      The specific targeting logic that Harmon describes. He states that tech companies like Google, Amazon, Meta, and x (twitter) are intentionally targeting Indigenous and rural communities as they have large amounts of space, access to resources, and that over 80% of the world's natural resources are contained within Indigenous lands. Which is mentioned before on the total amount of Lithium Deposits found. Also referencing some topics that we have learned in this class, such as the fact of cycling resources, allowing land to heal before it is harvested again. Because of these land caring practices, these companies see the rich resouce availability, and wish to only consume and monitize each part of it. He specifially relates how as a Citizen in the Muscogee area, how corporations have been coming to tribal leaders, convincing them to sign NDA's where no one other then them is allowed to view any details, until usually it is too late to prevent it. Harmon explains, corporations defend the NDA's as standard buisness practice, but he fights back. Saying that public infrastrucure that effects citizens should NOT be a trade secret. Rather he uses the direct quote, "It's a subversion of informed consent for the community". That puts the members in a bind, where only industry experts that understand this are being kept out of the loop, yet those that are unaware of the knowledge needed to make an informed descission are kept for that exact reason, to be guided into accepting these highly unfavorable terms. It's a system designed to never allow anyone but the company to benefit. Putting all of the Indigenous Views into jeaperdy. From caring for the land, to now allowing data centers to abuse it is a step in the wrong direction.  



</p>